In this regard, I or my daughter are lucky in that I got her later than most. She is just eleven years. It gave her dad just that more time to get his shit together so that she doesn't have to pay a huge price, like guilt, grief and all the other stuff. This does not mean that she will escape the effects of Vietnam, not by a long shot! What it means is what she walks away with are, hopefully, more positive in nature. We speak of Vietnam, but stuff that are age appropriate. I write constantly, so that when I am gone, she will have something to reflect on. Sorta like the audiotape idea. And through my writings, she will see how my perspective of my involvement in the war has evolved throughout my years. An example is that just lately, I have been remembering some events that I thought were long gone. I write them down. Five years from now, my perspective of these events will be different.<br><br>
Had my daughter been born twenty or even ten years ago, things would not have been as good as they are now. Then, my focus would have still been on 'Nam, not her.<br><br>
And Chet thought I was totally hopeless......... :)
